text: Oh wow i'm really happy this research is starting to get pooled
meds researchers (and cancer treatment research in the consumer space) tends to be ultra secretive in my experience (having worked at a place that was in competition with GE)
I think the work he is doing is intentionally combatting the secretive/proprietary status quo
thats so good. i was reading about the anonymized dataset that is genome + medical history
that you have to be a hospital researcher to get at
and i get that, but also wish there were better partnership opportunities

it would be interesting to figure a way to open that up that. I imagine there's a ton of sensitivity around even allowing access to anonymized medical data. Maybe it's a baby step towards something that's a little more inclusive.
when i was doing the epidemiology and outbreak detection stuff back in the day, it was surprisingly easy to get at anonymized ED data
i think once you get into imagery it starts getting very weird very fast
This sounds like what Jeremy wants to do
why didn't anyone tell me that?
it came up in a chat last week, not sure if it is general knowledge
